nization Find Federal Agencies Find Service Providers Our Programs SelectUSA Tech Select Global Women in Tech (SGWIT) Investment Advisory Council (IAC) Interagency Investment Working Group (IIWG) Research Center Investor Guide Industry Overview Hub Workforce Development Fact Sheets Reports and Publications Online Data Tools Let Our Experts Help About Select USA Services Contact Us Additional Resources State Business Incentives Database Careers and Internships News About Us Contact Us Search ITA Search Menu Search ITA Search For U.S. Businesses Export Solutions Overview Get Ready to Export Exporter Resources Client Success Stories Events and Webinars Research Center Overview Visual Data Center Research by Industry Research By Country Research By Region Trade Data and Analysis Public APIs Regulations & Agreements Overview U.S. Export Regulations Foreign Regulations Trade Agreements Resolve a Trade Problem Overview Resolve a Foreign Trade Barrier U.S. Antidumping & Countervailing Duties Facing a Foreign AD/CVD or Safeguard Investigation Fight Unfair Foreign Trade Subsidies Industry Monitoring & Analysis Protect Your Intellectual Property Advocating for U.S. Business Abroad Attend an Event Overview Trade Event Search Network & Learn at Events Meet Buyers at Events Trade Missions Services for Trade Event Organizers Foreign Direct Investment Attraction Events Let Our Experts Help Overview New Exporter Services Experienced Exporter Services Event Organizer Services Associations & EDO Services Rural Company Services Foreign-Trade Zones Partner with ITA BuyUSA Overview Find a Supplier - Textiles and Apparel Invest in the USA Make Connections Upcoming Events SelectUSA Investment Summit Find Economic Development Organization Find Federal Agencies Find Service Providers Our Programs SelectUSA Tech Select Global Women in Tech (SGWIT) Investment Advisory Council (IAC) Interagency Investment Working Group (IIWG) Research Center Investor Guide Industry Overview Hub Workforce Development Fact Sheets Reports and Publications Online Data Tools Let Our Experts Help About Select USA Services Contact Us Additional Resources State Business Incentives Database Careers and Internships News About Us Contact Us Home Country Commercial Guides Taiwan - Labeling/Marking Requirements Taiwan Country Commercial Guide Learn about the market conditions, opportunities, regulations, and business conditions in Taiwan, prepared by at U.S. Embassies worldwide by Commerce Department, State Department and other U.S. agencies’ professionals. Taiwan Country Commercial Guide Doing Business in Taiwan Market Overview Market Challenges Market Opportunities Market Entry Strategy Leading Sectors for US Exports & Investments Agricultural Sectors Biotechnologies Cybersecurity Education and Training Services Highly Automated and Autonomous Systems Quantum Technology Energy Generation and Storage Semiconductors including chip design for AI Space Technologies and Systems Travel and Tourism Customs, Regulations & Standards Trade Barriers Import Tariffs Import Requirements and Documentation Labeling/Marking Requirements U.S. Export Controls Temporary Entry Prohibited & Restricted Imports Customs Regulations Standards for Trade Trade Agreements Licensing Requirements for Professional Services Selling US Products & Services Distribution and Sales Channels eCommerce Selling Factors and Techniques Trade Financing Protecting Intellectual Property Selling to the Public Sector Digital Economy Digital Economy Business Travel Business Travel Investment Climate Statement Investment Climate Statement Select Country Guide Labeling/Marking Requirements Last published date: 2025-12-10 Taiwan’s Commodity Labeling Act stipulates that all commodities sold in Taiwan shall be labeled using the Chinese language and maybe be supplemented by English or another foreign language, provided the Chinese labeling is no less comprehensive than the product label written in the language-of-origin. In the event that the material contained within the commodity’s language-of-origin cannot be properly described in the Chinese language, such material may be labeled using international accepted words or symbols. Imports sold in Taiwan must be labeled with product information including the name of the commodity itself; the name, telephone number, and address of the producer or manufacturer; the commodity’s place of origin; and the name, telephone number, and address of the importer. The contact information for foreign companies or locations is not required to be written in Chinese. Product labels must also include the contents or composition of the commodity; major components/ingredients, or materials; and the net weight, volume or quantity, and measurements of the product. This content information must be labeled in Chinese and use metric units, however, labeling using both metric and non-metric units is also permitted. Furthermore, to be sold in Taiwan, all measuring instruments calibrated in non-metric units must also display their metric equivalents. If a product is hazardous or dangerous in nature, is related to health and safety, has special characteristics, requires special handling, or has a limited storage duration, it must also be labeled with the date of manufacture in the Chinese using either the Taiwan or Gregorian calendar, the expiration date or the term of validity, and other particulars as required by the Taiwan authorities. During shipping, all imported cargo must bear a mark of distinctive design, a set of three or more letters, or a combination of design and letters indelibly stenciled, stamped, or burned on the packing or on the cargo itself. For cargo packed in cases, boxes, crates, casks, drums, or cylinders, each container should also bear a separate number that cannot be repeated for two years. Bags or bales also must bear a non-recurring number, date, or set of three or more letters. In addition, each package of a consignment must be numbered consecutively. Numbering is not essential for large cargo lots except when packaged in cases, boxes, or crates, if each package of the consignment contains cargo of identical weight XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX Taiwan’s Commodity Labeling Act stipulates that all commodities sold in Taiwan shall be labeled using the Chinese language and may be supplemented', '{"source_registry_version":"2026-06-25","authority":"U.S. International Trade Administration","domain":"market_guide","tags":["labeling","marking","market-entry"],"format":"html","page_count":null,"parse_error":null}'::jsonb) on conflict (source_key, content_hash) do update set fetched_at = excluded.fetched_at, from_cache = excluded.from_cache, bytes = excluded.bytes, text_chars = excluded.text_chars, document_path = excluded.document_path, extract = excluded.extract, metadata = excluded.metadata;
